# Deployment

This app deploys with [Kamal](https://kamal-deploy.org/) — Docker-based, zero-downtime deploys to any VPS.

The production container runs two processes: Caddy on port 8080 serving the statically exported frontend (and proxying `/_event` websockets, `/up`, and `/api/*` to the backend), and the Reflex backend on port 8000.

## Prerequisites

- Docker installed locally
- Kamal installed locally (`gem install kamal`)
- A server (Ubuntu 22.04+ recommended) with SSH access
- A container registry account (GitHub Container Registry is configured by default)
- Optional: a domain name pointed at your server's IP (required for SSL)

## First-time setup

### 1. Configure your server and domain

Edit `config/deploy.yml`:

```yaml
servers:
  web:
    - 1.2.3.4              # your server IP

builder:
  args:
    API_URL: https://my-app.example.com   # public URL baked into the frontend

proxy:
  app_port: 8080
  # ssl: true                     # uncomment to enable SSL
  # host: my-app.example.com      # your domain
```

`API_URL` must match the public URL users will visit — the frontend uses it for the websocket connection and API calls. Without a domain, use `http://YOUR_SERVER_IP:8080`.

### 2. Set secrets

`.kamal/secrets` reads values from your environment — it contains only `$ENV` references and is safe to commit. Export the values before deploying:

```bash
export KAMAL_REGISTRY_PASSWORD=ghp_yourGitHubToken   # write:packages scope
export SMTP_USERNAME=your_smtp_username
export SMTP_PASSWORD=your_smtp_password
```

### 3. Configure email

Magic link sign-in emails need an SMTP provider in production. Uncomment and fill in `config/deploy.yml`:

```yaml
env:
  clear:
    MAILER_FROM_ADDRESS: noreply@my-app.example.com
    SMTP_ADDRESS: smtp.example.com
    SMTP_PORT: "587"
```

Until SMTP is configured, codes are logged to the container output (`kamal logs`).

### 4. Bootstrap the server

```bash
kamal setup
```

This installs Docker on the server, configures the proxy, and runs your first deploy.

### 5. Subsequent deploys

```bash
kamal deploy
# or
make deploy
```

## CI/CD (automatic deploys)

The `.github/workflows/deploy.yml` workflow deploys automatically on every push to `main`.

Required GitHub repository secrets:

| Secret | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `DEPLOY_KEY` | SSH private key with access to your server |
| `KAMAL_REGISTRY_PASSWORD` | GitHub token with `write:packages` scope |
| `SMTP_USERNAME` | SMTP username |
| `SMTP_PASSWORD` | SMTP password |

## Environment variables

| Variable | Required | Default | Description |
|----------|----------|---------|-------------|
| `DATABASE_URL` | No | `sqlite:////data/{{APP_MODULE}}.db` | SQLAlchemy database URL |
| `MAILER_FROM_ADDRESS` | No | `noreply@example.com` | Sender email |
| `SMTP_ADDRESS` | No | — | SMTP server host (codes are logged when unset) |
| `SMTP_PORT` | No | `587` | SMTP port |
| `SMTP_USERNAME` | No | — | SMTP username |
| `SMTP_PASSWORD` | No | — | SMTP password |

## Database

The SQLite database lives on the `{{APP_MODULE}}_data` Docker volume mounted at `/data` — it survives deploys and container restarts. WAL mode is enabled automatically (see `{{APP_MODULE}}/db.py`), so concurrent readers never block and concurrent writes queue via `busy_timeout`.

Migrations run automatically on container start (`bin/docker-entrypoint`).

To back up: `kamal server exec "docker run --rm -v {{APP_MODULE}}_data:/data -v /tmp:/backup alpine tar czf /backup/db.tar.gz /data"` and copy the archive off the server.

## Scaling note

This setup intentionally runs a **single backend process** — Reflex keeps per-client state in memory. That is plenty for most single-server apps. If you ever need multiple backend workers or servers, add Redis and set `REFLEX_REDIS_URL`; until then, don't.

## Useful Kamal commands

```bash
kamal logs              # tail production logs
kamal shell             # shell into the running container (alias)
kamal dbc               # sqlite3 console on the production database (alias)
kamal deploy            # deploy latest main
kamal rollback          # roll back to previous version
kamal app restart       # restart app containers
```

## Health check

Kamal monitors `GET /up` — the FastAPI app returns `200 OK` when ready.
If the health check fails after deploy, Kamal automatically rolls back.
